## 1. Semantic HTML Structure

### Use Proper HTML Elements

Always use semantic HTML5 elements instead of generic divs and spans:

```tsx
// ❌ Bad - Non-semantic
<div class="header">
  <div class="nav">
    <div class="nav-item">Home</div>
  </div>
</div>

// ✅ Good - Semantic
<header>
  <nav>
    <a href="/">Home</a>
  </nav>
</header>
```

### Semantic Element Reference

| Element     | Purpose                | When to Use                    |
| ----------- | ---------------------- | ------------------------------ |
| `<header>`  | Page/section header    | Top of page or section         |
| `<nav>`     | Navigation links       | Main navigation, footer nav    |
| `<main>`    | Main content           | Primary content (one per page) |
| `<article>` | Self-contained content | Blog posts, news articles      |
| `<section>` | Thematic grouping      | Content sections               |
| `<aside>`   | Tangential content     | Sidebars, related content      |
| `<footer>`  | Page/section footer    | Bottom of page or section      |

### Heading Hierarchy

Maintain proper heading order (h1 → h2 → h3):

```tsx
// ❌ Bad - Skips levels
<h1>Page Title</h1>
<h3>Section Title</h3> {/* Skipped h2 */}

// ✅ Good - Proper hierarchy
<h1>Page Title</h1>
<h2>Section Title</h2>
<h3>Subsection Title</h3>
```

**Rules:**

- One `<h1>` per page (typically the page title)
- Don't skip heading levels
- Don't use headings for styling (use CSS instead)

